-- Franklin Chief Johnson Gets 47% Pay Increase After Lifting Sales, Assets
-- B y   C h a r l e s   S t e i n
-- 2012-01-24T18:47:45Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-01-24/franklin-resources-chief-johnson-gets-47-pay-increase-after-lifting-sales.html
Franklin Resources Inc. (BEN) , manager of
the Franklin and Templeton mutual funds, paid Chief Executive
Officer Gregory Johnson $9.9 million in fiscal year 2011, a 47
percent increase from the previous year, as the firm
outperformed competitors.  Johnson boosted sales, earnings and assets under management
in the year ended Sept. 30, the  San Mateo , California-based firm
said in a filing today with the U.S. Securities and Exchange
Commission. Johnson’s salary increased 2.6 percent to $780,000.
His stock awards more than doubled to $6.4 million, according to
the proxy filing.  Vijay Advani, the firm’s head of global distribution,
received a 53 percent pay raise to $5.78 million, according to
the filing. Compensation for Jennifer M. Johnson, the chief
operating officer and Gregory Johnson’s sister, increased 20
percent to $3.39 million.  Franklin shares declined 11 percent in the 12 months ended
Sept. 30, 2011, compared with a decline of 19 percent for the
20-member  Standard & Poor’s  index of asset managers and custody
banks, data compiled by Bloomberg show.  Franklin attracted $3.1 billion in deposits in the quarter
ended Sept. 30 and $21.7 billion in the previous quarter, the
company reported. Investors added $13.4 billion to the $57
billion Templeton Global Bond Fund in 2011, the third most of
any U.S. mutual fund, according to Chicago-based Morningstar
Inc.  To contact the reporter on this story:
